<subSubSection id="079E653C537CFFB2FEA38137FE66FBE1" box="[151,462,1076,1103]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7537CFFB2FEA38137FE66FBE1" blockId="34.[151,1437,1076,1859]" box="[151,462,1076,1103]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FEA38137FE81FBE0" bold="true" box="[151,297,1076,1102]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Distribution</emphasis>
. SPA (
<quantity id="887C9B52537CFFB2FF428137FE6AFBE1" box="[374,450,1076,1103]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="m" value="1.0" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.0">0–2 m</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="079E653C537CFFB2FEF3815BFC7CF8EC" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7537CFFB2FEF3815BFE6FFA3C" blockId="34.[151,1437,1076,1859]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FEF3815BFE9CFBDC" bold="true" box="[199,308,1112,1138]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Remarks</emphasis>
. A.M. 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FFB5815BFDB8FBDD" author="Clark, A. M." box="[385,528,1112,1139]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="247 - 261" refId="ref29869" refString="Clark, A. M. (1976) Asterozoa from Amsterdam and St Paul Islands, southern Indian Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), 30, 247 - 261, pls. 1 - 2. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 2384" type="journal article" year="1976">Clark (1976)</bibRefCitation>
identified small amphiurids collected from the coastal zone around Île Saint-Paul and Île Amsterdam as the South African species 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FCF9817FFC0FFB38" authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[717,935,1148,1174]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FCF9817FFC0FFB38" box="[717,935,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Amphiura capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, apparently unaware that an earlier species 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FEA381A3FD0DFB14" authority="Marktanner-Turneretscher, 1887" authorityName="Marktanner-Turneretscher" authorityYear="1887" box="[151,677,1184,1210]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="brevispina">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FEA381A3FE86FB14" box="[151,302,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. brevispina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FF0C81A3FD0DFB14" author="Marktanner-Turneretscher, G." box="[312,677,1184,1210]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="291 - 316" refId="ref33630" refString="Marktanner-Turneretscher, G. (1887) Beschreibung neuer Ophiuriden und Bemerkungen zu bekannten. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 2, 291 - 316 pls. 12 - 13. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 29076" type="journal article" year="1887">Marktanner-Turneretscher, 1887</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
had been described from Île Saint-Paul on the Novara expedition in 1857 and later collected by the La Dive expedition in 1872 (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FD5781C7FBBAFB71" author="Koehler, R." box="[867,1042,1220,1247]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="279 - 351" refId="ref32252" refString="Koehler, R. (1907 b) Revision de la collection des Ophiures du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle Paris. Bulletin Scientique de la France et de la Belgique, 41, 279 - 351, pls. 10 - 14." type="journal article" year="1907">Koehler 1907b</bibRefCitation>
). The two species are very similar, having oblong proximally divergent radial shields, 1/6 dd in length, small disc scales, often sparser near the oral shields, DAPs slightly wider than long, one small tentacle scale, spear-head-shaped oral shields and a small conical adoral shield spine (distal oral papilla). There are generally 4–5 small arm spines at 
<quantity id="887C9B52537CFFB2FA628033FB1DFAE5" box="[1110,1205,1328,1355]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
dd, the middle ones slightly flattened and truncate. Large 
<quantity id="887C9B52537CFFB2FC0A8057FD24FAC1" box="[574,652,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
dd specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FD668057FC7AFAC0" authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[850,978,1364,1390]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FD668057FC7AFAC0" box="[850,978,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="37937627537CFFB2FA2C8057FB00FAC0" box="[1048,1192,1364,1390]" name="South Africa" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">South Africa</collectingCountry>
can have up to 7 arm spines (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FED8807BFE13FA3C" author="Olbers, J. M. &amp; Griffiths, C. L. &amp; O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Samyn, Y." box="[236,443,1400,1426]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refId="ref35203" refString="Olbers, J. M., Griffiths, C. L., O'Hara, T. D. &amp; Samyn, Y. (2019) Field guide to the brittle and basket stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) of South Africa. Brussels: Royal Belgium Institute of Natural Sciences." type="book" year="2019">
Olbers 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FF0B807AFEDFFA3C" box="[319,375,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7537CFFB2FEF3809FFB05F954" blockId="34.[151,1437,1076,1859]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FEF3809FFE33FA18" authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[199,411,1436,1462]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FEF3809FFE33FA18" box="[199,411,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Amphiura capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
broods its young(
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FC69809FFC88FA18" author="Mortensen, T." box="[605,800,1436,1462]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="215 - 400" refId="ref34370" refString="Mortensen, T. (1933 a) Echinoderms of South Africa (Asteroidea: Ophiuroidea). Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra Dansk Naturhistorisk Forening, 93, 215 - 400, pls. 8 - 19." type="journal article" year="1933">Mortensen1933a</bibRefCitation>
)and presumably 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FDE9809FFBC5FA18" authorityName="Marktanner-Turneretscher" authorityYear="1887" box="[989,1133,1436,1462]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="brevispina">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FDE9809FFBC5FA18" box="[989,1133,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A.brevispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does as well.Consequently, the common ancestor of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FF9180C3FD0AFA74" box="[421,674,1472,1498]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="capensis-brevispina">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FF9180C3FD0AFA74" box="[421,674,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. capensis-brevispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presumably rafted to SPA in kelp holdfasts or on wood. Interestingly, 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FEA380E7FEB0FA50" authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[151,280,1508,1534]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="capensis">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FEA380E7FEB0FA50" box="[151,280,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been collected from the remote island of 
<collectingCountry id="37937627537CFFB2FD6F80E7FBB6FA50" box="[859,1054,1508,1534]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Tristan da Cunha</collectingCountry>
in the South Atlantic (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FB1780E7FF7BF98C" author="Mortensen, T." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref34498" refString="Mortensen, T. (1941) Echinoderms of Tristan da Cunha. Results of the Norwegian Scientific Expedition to Tristan da Cunha 1937 - 1938, 7, 1 - 10, pl. 1." type="journal article" year="1941">Mortensen 1941</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately, we do not have DNA data for these populations. However, phylogeographic data is available for the benthic egg-laying asteroid 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FC06832FFC26F9E9" authority="(Lamarck)" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[562,910,1580,1607]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Parvulastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="exigua">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FC06832FFCA6F9E8" box="[562,782,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Parvulastra exigua</emphasis>
(Lamarck)
</taxonomicName>
with a similar distribution (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FAEC832FFA30F9E8" author="Hart, M. W. &amp; Keever, C. C. &amp; Dartnall, A. J. &amp; Byrne, M." box="[1240,1432,1580,1606]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="158 - 167" refId="ref31575" refString="Hart, M. W., Keever, C. C., Dartnall, A. J. &amp; Byrne, M. (2006) Morphological and genetic variation indicate cryptic species within Lamarck's little sea star, Parvulastra (= Patiriella) exigua. Biological Bulletin, 210, 158 - 167. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 4134604" type="journal article" year="2006">
Hart 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FB22832EFAFAF9E8" box="[1302,1362,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FEA38352FE29F9C4" author="Waters, J. M. &amp; Roy, M. S." box="[151,385,1616,1643]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="18 - 24" refId="ref36793" refString="Waters, J. M. &amp; Roy, M. S. (2004) Out of Africa: The Slow Train to Australasia. Systematic Biology, 53, 18 - 24. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 10635150490264671" type="journal article" year="2004">Waters &amp; Roy 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Network analyses of COI sequences showed that 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FDFB8353FBFDF9C4" authorityName="O'Loughlin in O'Loughlin &amp; Waters" authorityYear="2004" box="[975,1109,1616,1642]" class="Asteroidea" family="Asterinidae" genus="Parvulastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FDFB8353FBFDF9C4" box="[975,1109,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Parvulastra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens from Amsterdam Island were phylogenetically distinct from clades on the South African and Australian coasts (
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FAEE8377FA30F920" author="Hart, M. W. &amp; Keever, C. C. &amp; Dartnall, A. J. &amp; Byrne, M." box="[1242,1432,1652,1678]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="158 - 167" refId="ref31575" refString="Hart, M. W., Keever, C. C., Dartnall, A. J. &amp; Byrne, M. (2006) Morphological and genetic variation indicate cryptic species within Lamarck's little sea star, Parvulastra (= Patiriella) exigua. Biological Bulletin, 210, 158 - 167. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 4134604" type="journal article" year="2006">
Hart 
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FB238376FAFBF920" box="[1303,1363,1652,1678]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46537CFFB2FEA3839AFE2EF91C" author="Waters, J. M. &amp; Roy, M. S." box="[151,390,1688,1715]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="18 - 24" refId="ref36793" refString="Waters, J. M. &amp; Roy, M. S. (2004) Out of Africa: The Slow Train to Australasia. Systematic Biology, 53, 18 - 24. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 10635150490264671" type="journal article" year="2004">Waters &amp; Roy 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Presumably, long distance rafting is an infrequent event allowing the island populations to diverge from their African source populations. Until there is genetic data for this 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FA5783BFFB7BF978" authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1843" box="[1123,1235,1724,1750]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FA5783BFFB7BF978" box="[1123,1235,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Amphiura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the conservative approach is taken here of recognising 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FC7583E3FD7DF954" authorityName="Marktanner-Turneretscher" authorityYear="1887" box="[577,725,1760,1786]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="brevispina">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FC7583E3FD7DF954" box="[577,725,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. brevispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an endemic species of the SPA islands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7537CFFB2FEF38206FC7CF8EC" blockId="34.[151,1437,1076,1859]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Except for the next species, the numerous other 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34537CFFB2FCC08207FCCCF8B0" authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1843" box="[756,868,1796,1822]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Amphiuridae" genus="Amphiura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphilepidida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5537CFFB2FCC08207FCCCF8B0" box="[756,868,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Amphiura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens (&lt;
<quantity id="887C9B52537CFFB2FA378207FBF5F8B1" box="[1027,1117,1796,1823]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
dd) collected by the MD50 expedition (
<tableCitation id="0206030C537CFFB2FF28822BFEC6F8EC" box="[284,366,1832,1858]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[150,238,478,504]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. List of ophiuroids collected by the MD50 expedition." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1BFB663F535AFF94FEA284DDFCE2FE56" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" tableUuid="1BFB663F535AFF94FEA284DDFCE2FE56">Table 1</tableCitation>
) were small and damaged and not readily identifiable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
